# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: two-three-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] In computer science, a **2–3–4 tree** (also called a **2–4 tree**) is a self-balancing data structure that can be used to implement dictionaries.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] 2–3–4 trees are B-trees of order 4; like B-trees in general, they can search, insert and delete in O(log *n*) time.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] One property of a 2–3–4 tree is that all external nodes are at the same depth.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] 2–3–4 trees are closely related to red–black trees by interpreting red links (that is, links to red children) as internal links of 3-nodes and 4-nodes, although this correspondence is not one-to-one.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] Left-leaning red–black trees restrict red–black trees by forbidding nodes with a single red right child, which yields a one-to-one correspondence between left-leaning red–black trees and 2–3–4 trees.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] Find the child whose interval contains the value to be inserted.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] If that child is a leaf, insert the value into the child node and finish.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] The simplest possibility to delete an element is to just leave the element there and mark it as "deleted", adapting the previous algorithms so that deleted elements are ignored.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] Deleted elements can then be re-used by overwriting them when performing an insertion later.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] However, the drawback of this method is that the size of the tree does not decrease.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] If a large proportion of the elements of the tree are deleted, then the tree will become much larger than the current size of the stored elements, and the performance of other operations will be adversely affected by the deleted elements.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] If the parent is a 2-node and the sibling is also a 2-node, combine all three elements to form a new 4-node and shorten the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] (This rule can only trigger if the parent 2-node is the root, since all other 2-nodes along the way will have been modified to not be 2-nodes.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] Once the sought value is reached, it can now be placed at the removed entry's location without a problem because we have ensured that the leaf node has more than 1 key.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] Deletion in a 2–3–4 tree is O(log n), assuming transfer and fusion run in constant time (O(1)).
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-4-tree] Since 2–3–4 trees are similar in structure to red–black trees, parallel algorithms for red–black trees can be applied to 2–3–4 trees as well.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] In computer science, a **2–3 tree** is a tree data structure, where every node with children (internal node) has either two children (2-node) and one data element or three children (3-node) and two data elements.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Nodes on the outside of the tree (leaf nodes) have no children and one or two data elements.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] 2–3 trees were invented by John Hopcroft in 1970.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] 2–3 trees are required to be balanced, meaning that each leaf is at the same level.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] It follows that each right, center, and left subtree of a node contains the same or close to the same amount of data.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] We say that an internal node is a **2-node** if it has *one* data element and *two* children.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] We say that an internal node is a **3-node** if it has *two* data elements and *three* children.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] A **4-node**, with three data elements, may be temporarily created during manipulation of the tree but is never persistently stored in the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Searching for an item in a 2–3 tree is similar to searching for an item in a binary search tree.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Since the data elements in each node are ordered, a search function will be directed to the correct subtree and eventually to the correct node which contains the item.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Suppose t is a 2-node with left child p and right child q.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Suppose t is a 3-node with left child p, middle child q, and right child r.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Let a and b be the two data elements of t, where $a<b$ .
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Insertion maintains the balanced property of the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] To insert into a 2-node, the new key is added to the 2-node in the appropriate order.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] To insert into a 3-node, more work may be required depending on the location of the 3-node.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] If the tree consists only of a 3-node, the node is split into three 2-nodes with the appropriate keys and children.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] If the target node is a 3-node whose parent is a 2-node, the key is inserted into the 3-node to create a temporary 4-node.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] In the illustration, the key 10 is inserted into the 2-node with 6 and 9.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] The middle key is 9, and is promoted to the parent 2-node.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] This leaves a 3-node of 6 and 10, which is split to be two 2-nodes held as children of the parent 3-node.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] If the target node is a 3-node and the parent is a 3-node, a temporary 4-node is created then split as above.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] This process continues up the tree to the root.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] If the root must be split, then the process of a single 3-node is followed: a temporary 4-node root is split into three 2-nodes, one of which is considered to be the root.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] This operation grows the height of the tree by one.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Deleting a key from a non-leaf node can be done by replacing it by its immediate predecessor or successor, and then deleting the predecessor or successor from a leaf node.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Deleting a key from a leaf node is easy if the leaf is a 3-node.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Otherwise, it may require creating a temporary 1-node which may be absorbed by reorganizing the tree, or it may repeatedly travel upwards before it can be absorbed, as a temporary 4-node may in the case of insertion.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Alternatively, it's possible to use an algorithm which is both top-down and bottom-up, creating temporary 4-nodes on the way down that are then destroyed as you travel back up.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Deletion methods are explained in more detail in the references.
[src:two-three-tree/2-3-tree] Since 2–3 trees are similar in structure to red–black trees, parallel algorithms for red–black trees can be applied to 2–3 trees as well.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In computer science, a **B-tree** is a self-balancing tree data structure that maintains sorted data and allows searches, sequential access, insertions, and deletions in logarithmic time.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The B-tree generalizes the binary search tree, allowing nodes to have more than two children.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] By allowing more children under one node than a regular self-balancing binary search tree, the B-tree reduces the height of the tree and puts the data in fewer separate blocks.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] This is especially important for trees stored in secondary storage (e.g., disk drives), as these systems have relatively high latency and work with relatively large blocks of data, hence the B-tree's use in databases and file systems.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] This remains a major advantage when the tree is stored in memory, as modern computer systems rely heavily on CPU caches.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Compared to reading from the cache, reading from memory after a cache miss costs significant time.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] While working at Boeing Research Labs, Rudolf Bayer and Edward M.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] McCreight invented B-trees to efficiently manage index pages for large random-access files.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Their basic assumption was that indices would be so voluminous that only small chunks of the tree could fit in the main memory.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight's paper *Organization and maintenance of large ordered indices* was first circulated in July 1970 and later published in *Acta Informatica*.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight never explained what, if anything, the *B* stands for; *Boeing*, *balanced*, *between*, *broad*, *bushy*, and *Bayer* have been suggested.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Every node, except for the root and the leaves, has at least ⌈*m*/2⌉ children.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The root node has at least two children unless it is a leaf.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A non-leaf node with *k* children contains *k*−1 keys.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The keys of each non-leaf node act as separation values that divide its subtrees.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] For example, if an internal node has 3 child nodes (or subtrees), then it must have 2 keys: *a*1 and *a*2.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] All values in the leftmost subtree will be less than *a*1, all values in the middle subtree will be between *a*1 and *a*2, and all values in the rightmost subtree will be greater than *a*2.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] ) are all nodes except for leaf nodes and the root node.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] They are usually represented as an ordered set of elements and child pointers.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] −1; therefore, each internal node is at least half full.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] implies that two half-full nodes can be joined to make a legal node, and one full node can be split into two legal nodes (if there's room to push one element up into the parent).
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] These properties make it possible to delete and insert new values into a B-tree while also adjusting the tree to preserve its properties.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The root node's number of children has the same upper limit as internal nodes but has no lower limit.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] −1 elements in the entire tree, the root will be the only node in the tree with no children at all.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In Knuth's terminology, the "leaf" nodes are the actual data objects/chunks.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] /2-1 if they are not the root) and pointers (one for each key) to nodes carrying the data objects/chunks.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A B-tree of depth *n*+1 can hold about *U* times as many items as a B-tree of depth *n*, but the cost of search, insert, and delete operations grows with the depth of the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] As with any balanced tree, the cost grows much more slowly than the number of elements.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Some balanced trees store values only at leaf nodes and use different kinds of nodes for leaf nodes and internal nodes.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] B-trees keep values in every node in the tree except leaf nodes.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The literature on B-trees is not uniform in its terminology.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight (1972), Comer (1979), and others define the **order** of a B-tree as the minimum number of keys in a non-root node.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Folk and Zoellick point out that terminology is ambiguous because the maximum number of keys is unclear.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] An order 3 B-tree might hold a maximum of 6 keys or a maximum of 7 keys.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Knuth (1998) avoids the problem by defining the **order** to be the maximum number of children (which is one more than the maximum number of keys).
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight (1972) considered the leaf level to be the lowest level of keys, but Knuth considered the leaf level to be one level below the lowest keys.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] There are many possible implementation choices.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In some designs, the leaves may hold the entire data record; in other designs, the leaves may only hold pointers to the data record.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Those choices are not fundamental to the idea of a B-tree.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] For simplicity, most authors assume there is a fixed number of keys that fit in a node.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The basic assumption is that the key size and node size are both fixed.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In practice, variable-length keys may be employed.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] As with other trees, B-trees can be represented as a collection of three types of nodes: *root*, *internal* (a.k.a. interior), and *leaf*.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] To maintain the predefined range of child nodes, internal nodes may be joined or split.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Usually, the number of keys is chosen to vary between d and $2d$ , where d is the minimum number of keys, and $d+1$ is the minimum degree or branching factor of the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The factor of 2 will guarantee that nodes can be split or combined.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If an internal node has $2d$ keys, then adding a key to that node can be accomplished by splitting the hypothetical $2d+1$ key node into two d key nodes and moving the key that would have been in the middle to the parent node.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Each split node has the required minimum number of keys.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Similarly, if an internal node and its neighbor each have d keys, then a key may be deleted from the internal node by combining it with its neighbor.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Deleting the key would make the internal node have $d-1$ keys; joining the neighbor would add d keys plus one more key brought down from the neighbor's parent.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The result is an entirely full node of $2d$ keys.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A B-tree is kept balanced after insertion by splitting a would-be overfilled node, of $2d+1$ keys, into two d-key siblings and inserting the mid-value key into the parent.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Depth only increases when the root is split, maintaining balance.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Similarly, a B-tree is kept balanced after deletion by merging or redistributing keys among siblings to maintain the d-key minimum for non-root nodes.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A merger reduces the number of keys in the parent, potentially forcing it to merge or redistribute keys with its siblings, and so on.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The only change in depth occurs when the root has two children, of d and (transitionally) $d-1$ keys, in which case the two siblings and parent are merged, reducing the depth by one.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] This depth will increase slowly as elements are added to the tree, but an increase in the overall depth is infrequent, and results in all leaf nodes being one more node farther away from the root.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Because a range of child nodes is permitted, B-trees do not need re-balancing as frequently as other self-balancing search trees, but may waste some space since nodes are not entirely full.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] B-trees have substantial advantages over alternative implementations when the time to access the data of a node greatly exceeds the time spent processing that data, because the cost of accessing the node may then be amortized over multiple operations within the node.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] This usually occurs when the node data are stored in secondary storage, such as disk drives.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] By maximizing the number of keys within each internal node, the height of the tree decreases, and the number of expensive node accesses is reduced.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In addition, rebalancing of the tree occurs less frequently.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The maximum number of child nodes depends on the information that must be stored for each child node and the size of a full disk block or an analogous size in secondary storage.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] While 2–3 B-trees are easier to explain, practical B-trees using secondary storage need a large number of child nodes to improve performance.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The term **B-tree** may refer to a specific design or a general class of designs.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In the narrow sense, a B-tree stores keys in its internal nodes but need not store those keys in the records at the leaves.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The general class includes variations such as the B+ tree, the B* tree and the B*+ tree.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Sorting and searching algorithms can be characterized by the number of comparison operations that must be performed using order notation.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A binary search of a sorted table with N records, for example, can be done in roughly ⌈ log2 *N* ⌉ comparisons.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If the table had 1,000,000 records, then a specific record could be located with at most 20 comparisons: ⌈ log2 (1,000,000) ⌉ = 20.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Large databases have historically been kept on disk drives.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The time required to read a record on a disk drive far exceeds the time needed to compare keys once the record is available due to seek time and rotational delay.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The seek time may be 0 to 20 or more milliseconds, and the rotational delay averages about half the rotation period.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] For a 7200 RPM drive, the rotation period is 8.33 milliseconds.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] For a drive such as the Seagate ST3500320NS, the track-to-track seek time is 0.8 milliseconds and the average reading seek time is 8.5 milliseconds.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] For simplicity, assume reading from disk takes about 10 milliseconds.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The time required to locate one record out of a million in the example above would be 20 disk reads, each taking 10 milliseconds, which equals 0.2 seconds.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The search time is reduced because individual records are grouped together in a disk **block**.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A disk block might be 16 kilobytes in size.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If each record is 160 bytes, then 100 records could be stored in each block.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The disk read time above was actually for an entire block.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Once the disk head is in position, one or more disk blocks can be read with little delay.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] With 100 records per block, the last 6 or so comparisons don't need to do any disk reads—the comparisons are all within the last disk block read.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] To speed up the search further, the time to do the first 13 to 14 comparisons (which each required disk access) must be reduced.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A B-tree index can be used to improve performance.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A B-tree index creates a multi-level tree structure that breaks a database down into fixed-size blocks or pages.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Each level of this tree can be used to link those pages via an address location, allowing one page (known as a node, or internal page) to refer to another with leaf pages at the lowest level.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] One page is typically the starting point of the tree, or the "root".
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] This is where the search for a particular key would begin, traversing a path that terminates in a leaf.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Most pages in this structure will be leaf pages which refer to specific table rows.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Because each node (or internal page) can have more than two children, a B-tree index will usually have a shorter height (the distance from the root to the farthest leaf) than a Binary Search Tree.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In the example above, initial disk reads narrowed the search range by a factor of two.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] That can be improved by creating an auxiliary index that contains the first record in each disk block (sometimes called a sparse index).
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] This auxiliary index would be 1% of the size of the original database, but it can be searched quickly.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Finding an entry in the auxiliary index would tell us which block to search in the main database; after searching the auxiliary index, we would have to search only that one block of the main database—at a cost of one more disk read.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In the above example, the index would hold 10,000 entries and would take at most 14 comparisons to return a result.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Like the main database, the last six or so comparisons in the auxiliary index would be on the same disk block.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The index could be searched in about eight disk reads, and the desired record could be accessed in 9 disk reads.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Creating an auxiliary index can be repeated to make an auxiliary index to the auxiliary index.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] That would create an aux-aux index that would need only 100 entries and would fit in one disk block.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Instead of reading 14 disk blocks to find the desired record, we only need to read 3 blocks.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] This blocking is the core idea behind the creation of the B-tree, where disk blocks form a hierarchy of levels to make up the index.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Reading and searching the first (and only) block of the aux-aux index, which is the root of the tree, identifies the relevant block in aux-index in the level below.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Reading and searching that aux-index block identifies the relevant block to read until the final level, known as the leaf level, identifies a record in the main database.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Instead of 150 milliseconds, we need only 30 milliseconds to get the record.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The auxiliary indices have turned the search problem from a binary search requiring roughly log2 *N* disk reads to one requiring only log*b* *N* disk reads where b is the blocking factor (the number of entries per block: *b* = 100 entries per block in our example; log100 1,000,000 = 3 reads).
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In practice, if the main database is being frequently searched, the aux-aux index and much of the aux index may reside in a disk cache, so they would not incur a disk read.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The B-tree remains the standard index implementation in almost all relational databases, and many nonrelational databases use it as well.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If the database does not change, then compiling the index is simple to do, and the index need never be changed.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If there are changes, managing the database and its index requires additional computation.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Deleting records from a database is relatively easy.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The index can stay the same, and the record can just be marked as deleted.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If there are a large number of lazy deletions, then searching and storage become less efficient.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Insertions can be very slow in a sorted sequential file because room for the inserted record must be made.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Inserting a record before the first record requires shifting all of the records down one.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Such an operation is just too expensive to be practical.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Instead of densely packing all the records in a block, the block can have some free space to allow for subsequent insertions.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Those spaces would be marked as if they were "deleted" records.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Both insertions and deletions are fast as long as space is available on a block.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If an insertion won't fit on the block, then some free space on some nearby block must be found and the auxiliary indices adjusted.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The best case is that enough space is available nearby so that the amount of block reorganization can be minimized.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Alternatively, some out-of-sequence disk blocks may be used.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The B-tree uses all of the ideas described above.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In addition, a B-tree minimizes waste by making sure the interior nodes are at least half full.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A B-tree can handle an arbitrary number of insertions and deletions.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Let *h* ≥ –1 be the height of the classic B-tree (see Tree (data structure) § Terminology for the tree height definition).
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Let *n* ≥ 0 be the number of entries in the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Let *m* be the maximum number of children a node can have.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] It can be shown (by induction for example) that a B-tree of height *h* with all its nodes completely filled has *n* = *m**h*+1–1 entries.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Let d be the minimum number of children an internal (non-root) node must have.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Searching is similar to searching a binary search tree.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Starting at the root, the tree is recursively traversed from top to bottom.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] At each level, the search reduces its field of view to the child pointer (subtree) whose range includes the search value.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A subtree's range is defined by the values, or keys, contained in its parent node.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] These limiting values are also known as separation values.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Binary search is typically (but not necessarily) used within nodes to find the separation values and child tree of interest.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] To insert a new element, search the tree to find the leaf node where the new element should be added.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Values less than the median are put in the new left node, and values greater than the median are put in the new right node, with the median acting as a separation value.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The separation value is inserted in the node's parent, which may cause it to be split, and so on.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If the node has no parent (i.e., the node was the root), create a new root above this node (increasing the height of the tree).
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If the splitting goes all the way up to the root, it creates a new root with a single separator value and two children, which is why the lower bound on the size of internal nodes does not apply to the root.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The maximum number of elements per node is *U*−1.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] When a node is split, one element moves to the parent, but one element is added.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] So, it must be possible to divide the maximum number *U*−1 of elements into two legal nodes.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If this number is odd, then *U*=2*L* and one of the new nodes contains (*U*−2)/2 = *L*−1 elements, and hence is a legal node, and the other contains one more element, and hence it is legal too.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If *U*−1 is even, then *U*=2*L*−1, so there are 2*L*−2 elements in the node.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Half of this number is *L*−1, which is the minimum number of elements allowed per node.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] An alternative algorithm supports a single pass down the tree from the root to the node where the insertion will take place, splitting any full nodes encountered on the way pre-emptively.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] This prevents the need to recall the parent nodes into memory, which may be expensive if the nodes are on secondary storage.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] However, to use this algorithm, we must be able to send one element to the parent and split the remaining *U*−2 elements into two legal nodes, without adding a new element.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] This requires *U* = 2*L* rather than *U* = 2*L*−1, which accounts for why some textbooks impose this requirement in defining B-trees.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] There are two popular strategies for deletion from a B-tree.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Do a single pass down the tree, but before entering (visiting) a node, restructure the tree so that once the key to be deleted is encountered, it can be deleted without triggering the need for any further restructuring.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The algorithm below uses the former strategy.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Deleting an element may put its node under the minimum number of elements and children.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The procedures for these cases are listed below.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If the value is in a leaf node, simply delete it from the node.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If underflow happens, rebalance the tree as described in the section "Rebalancing after deletion" below.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Each element in an internal node acts as a separation value for two subtrees; we need to find a replacement for separation.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Note that the largest element in the left subtree is still less than the separator.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Likewise, the smallest element in the right subtree is still greater than the separator.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Both of those elements are in leaf nodes, and either one can be the new separator for the two subtrees.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The previous step deleted an element (the new separator) from a leaf node.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If that leaf node is now deficient (has fewer than the required number of nodes), then rebalance the tree starting from the leaf node.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Rebalancing starts from a leaf and proceeds toward the root until the tree is balanced.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If deleting an element from a node has brought it under the minimum size, then some elements must be redistributed to bring all nodes up to the minimum.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Usually, the redistribution involves moving an element from a sibling node that has more than the minimum number of nodes.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] That redistribution operation is called a **rotation**.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If no sibling can spare an element, then the deficient node must be **merged** with a sibling.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The merge causes the parent to lose a separator element, so the parent may become deficient and need rebalancing.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The merging and rebalancing may continue all the way to the root.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Since the minimum element count doesn't apply to the root, making the root be the only deficient node is not a problem.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] While freshly loaded databases tend to have good sequential behaviour, this behaviour becomes increasingly difficult to maintain as a database grows, resulting in more random I/O and performance challenges.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A common special case is adding a large amount of *pre-sorted* data into an initially empty B-tree.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] While it is quite possible to simply perform a series of successive inserts, inserting sorted data results in a tree composed almost entirely of half-full nodes.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Instead, a special "bulk loading" algorithm can be used to produce a more efficient tree with a higher branching factor.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] When the input is sorted, all insertions are at the rightmost edge of the tree, and in particular any time a node is split, we are guaranteed that no more insertions will take place in the left half.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] When bulk loading, we take advantage of this, and instead of splitting overfull nodes evenly, split them as *unevenly* as possible: leave the left node completely full and create a right node with zero keys and one child (in violation of the usual B-tree rules).
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] At the end of bulk loading, the tree is composed almost entirely of completely full nodes; only the rightmost node on each level may be less than full.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Because those nodes may also be less than *half* full, to re-establish the normal B-tree rules, combine such nodes with their (guaranteed full) left siblings and divide the keys to produce two nodes at least half full.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The only node which lacks a full left sibling is the root, which is permitted to be less than half full.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In addition to its use in databases, the B-tree (or § Variants) is also used in filesystems to allow quick random access to an arbitrary block in a particular file.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The basic problem is turning the file block i address into a disk block address.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Some early operating systems, and some highly specialized ones, required the application to allocate the maximum size of a file when the file was created.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The file can then be allocated as contiguous disk blocks.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In that case, to convert the file block address i into a disk block address, the operating system simply adds the file block address i to the address of the first disk block constituting the file.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The scheme is simple, but the file cannot exceed its created size.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] All modern, mainstream operating systems allow a file to grow.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The resulting disk blocks may not be contiguous, so mapping logical blocks to physical blocks is more involved.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] MS-DOS, for example, used a simple File Allocation Table (FAT).
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The FAT has an entry for each disk block, and that entry identifies whether its block is used by a file and if so, which block (if any) is the next disk block of the same file.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] So, the allocation of each file is represented as a linked list in the table.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In order to find the disk address of file block i , the operating system (or disk utility) must sequentially follow the file's linked list in the FAT.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Worse, to find a free disk block, it must sequentially scan the FAT.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] For MS-DOS, that was not a huge penalty because the disks and files were small and the FAT had few entries and relatively short file chains.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In the FAT12 filesystem (used on floppy disks and early hard disks), there were no more than 4,080 entries, and the FAT would usually be resident in memory.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] As disks got bigger, the FAT architecture began to confront penalties.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] On a large disk using FAT, it may be necessary to perform disk reads to learn the disk location of a file block to be read or written.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] TOPS-20 used a 0 to 2 level tree that has similarities to a B-tree.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If the file fit in a 512 (29) word block, then the file directory would point to that physical disk block.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If the file fit in 218 words, then the directory would point to an aux index; the 512 words of that index would either be NULL (the block isn't allocated) or point to the physical address of the block.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] If the file fit in 227 words, then the directory would point to a block holding an aux-aux index; each entry would either be NULL or point to an aux index.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Consequently, the physical disk block for a 227 word file could be located in two disk reads and read on the third.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Apple's filesystem HFS+ and APFS, Microsoft's NTFS, AIX (jfs2) and some Linux filesystems, such as Bcachefs, Btrfs and ext4, use B-trees.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] B*-trees are used in the HFS and Reiser4 file systems.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] DragonFly BSD's HAMMER file system uses a modified B+-tree.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A B-tree grows slower with growing data amount, than the linearity of a linked list.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Compared to a skip list, both structures have the same performance, but the B-tree scales better for growing *n*.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A T-tree, for main memory database systems, is similar but more compact.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Lehman and Yao showed that all the read locks could be avoided (and thus concurrent access greatly improved) by linking the tree blocks at each level together with a "next" pointer.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] This results in a tree structure where both insertion and search operations descend from the root to the leaf.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Write locks are only required as a tree block is modified.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] This maximizes access concurrency by multiple users, an important consideration for databases and/or other B-tree-based ISAM storage methods.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The cost associated with this improvement is that empty pages cannot be removed from the btree during normal operations.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] United States Patent 5283894, granted in 1994, appears to show a way to use a 'Meta Access Method' to allow concurrent B+ tree access and modification without locks.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] The technique accesses the tree 'upwards' for both searches and updates by means of additional in-memory indexes that point at the blocks in each level in the block cache.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] No reorganization for deletes is needed and there are no 'next' pointers in each block as in Lehman and Yao.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] Since B-trees are similar in structure to red-black trees, parallel algorithms for red-black trees can be applied to B-trees as well.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] A Maple tree is a B-tree developed for use in the Linux kernel to reduce lock contention in virtual memory management.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] (a,b)-trees are generalizations of B-trees.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] B-trees require that each internal node have a minimum of $\lfloor K/2\rfloor +1$ children and a maximum of K children, for some preset value of K .
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In contrast, an (a,b)-tree allows the minimum number of children for an internal node to be set arbitrarily low.
[src:two-three-tree/b-tree] In an (a,b)-tree, each internal node has between a and b children, for some preset values of a and b.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] In computer science, a **binary search tree** (**BST**), also called an **ordered** or **sorted binary tree**, is a rooted binary tree data structure with the key of each internal node being greater than all the keys in the respective node's left subtree and less than the ones in its right subtree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The time complexity of operations on the binary search tree is linear with respect to the height of the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees allow binary search for fast lookup, addition, and removal of data items.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Since the nodes in a BST are laid out so that each comparison skips about half of the remaining tree, the lookup performance is proportional to that of binary logarithm.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] BSTs were devised in the 1960s for the problem of efficient storage of labeled data and are attributed to Conway Berners-Lee and David Wheeler.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The performance of a binary search tree is dependent on the order of insertion of the nodes into the tree since arbitrary insertions may lead to degeneracy; several variations of the binary search tree can be built with guaranteed worst-case performance.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The basic operations include: search, traversal, insert and delete.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] BSTs with guaranteed worst-case complexities perform better than an unsorted array, which would require linear search time.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The complexity analysis of BST shows that, on average, the insert, delete and search takes $\Theta (\log n)$ for n nodes.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] In the worst case, they degrade to that of a singly linked list: $O(n)$ .
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] To address the boundless increase of the tree height with arbitrary insertions and deletions, self-balancing variants of BSTs are introduced to bound the worst lookup complexity to that of the binary logarithm.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] AVL trees were the first self-balancing binary search trees, invented in 1962 by Georgy Adelson-Velsky and Evgenii Landis.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees can be used to implement abstract data types such as dynamic sets, lookup tables and priority queues, and used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The binary search tree algorithm was discovered independently by several researchers, including P.F.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Windley, Andrew Donald Booth, Andrew Colin, Thomas N.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The algorithm is attributed to Conway Berners-Lee and David Wheeler, who used it for storing labeled data in magnetic tapes in 1960.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] One of the earliest and popular binary search tree algorithm is that of Hibbard.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The time complexity of a binary search tree increases boundlessly with the tree height if the nodes are inserted in an arbitrary order, therefore self-balancing binary search trees were introduced to bound the height of the tree to $O(\log n)$ .
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Various **height-balanced** binary search trees were introduced to confine the tree height, such as AVL trees, Treaps, and red–black trees.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are also efficacious in sortings and search algorithms.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are also a fundamental data structure used in construction of abstract data structures such as sets, multisets, and associative arrays.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Searching in a binary search tree for a specific key can be programmed recursively or iteratively.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Searching begins by examining the root node.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] If the tree is nil, the key being searched for does not exist in the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Otherwise, if the key equals that of the root, the search is successful and the node is returned.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] If the key is less than that of the root, the search proceeds by examining the left subtree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Similarly, if the key is greater than that of the root, the search proceeds by examining the right subtree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] This process is repeated until the key is found or the remaining subtree is ${\text{nil}}$ .
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] If the searched key is not found after a ${\text{nil}}$ subtree is reached, then the key is not present in the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode implements the BST search procedure through recursion.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The recursive procedure continues until a ${\text{nil}}$ or the ${\text{key}}$ being searched for are encountered.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The recursive version of the search can be "unrolled" into a while loop.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] On most machines, the iterative version is found to be more efficient.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Since the search may proceed till some leaf node, the running time complexity of BST search is $O(h)$ where h is the height of the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] However, the worst case for BST search is $O(n)$ where n is the total number of nodes in the BST, because an unbalanced BST may degenerate to a linked list.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] However, if the BST is height-balanced the height is $O(\log n)$ .
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] For certain operations, given a node ${\text{x}}$ , finding the successor or predecessor of ${\text{x}}$ is crucial.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Assuming all the keys of a BST are distinct, the successor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST is the node with the smallest key greater than ${\text{x}}$ 's key.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] On the other hand, the predecessor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST is the node with the largest key smaller than ${\text{x}}$ 's key.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode finds the successor and predecessor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Operations such as finding a node in a BST whose key is the maximum or minimum are critical in certain operations, such as determining the successor and predecessor of nodes.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Following is the pseudocode for the operations.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Operations such as insertion and deletion cause the BST representation to change dynamically.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The data structure must be modified in such a way that the properties of BST continue to hold.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] New nodes are inserted as leaf nodes in the BST.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Following is an iterative implementation of the insertion operation.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The procedure maintains a "trailing pointer" ${\text{y}}$ as a parent of ${\text{x}}$ .
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] After initialization on line 2, the **while** loop along lines 4-11 causes the pointers to be updated.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] If ${\text{y}}$ is ${\text{nil}}$ , the BST is empty, thus ${\text{z}}$ is inserted as the root node of the binary search tree ${\text{T}}$ , if it is not ${\text{nil}}$ , insertion proceeds by comparing the keys to that of ${\text{y}}$ on the lines 15-19 and the node is inserted accordingly.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] If ${\text{Z}}$ has only one child, the child node of ${\text{Z}}$ gets elevated by modifying the parent node of ${\text{Z}}$ to point to the child node, consequently taking ${\text{Z}}$ 's position in the tree, as shown in (b) and (c).
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] If ${\text{Y}}$ lies within ${\text{Z}}$ 's right subtree but is not ${\text{Z}}$ 's right child, as shown in (e), ${\text{Y}}$ first gets replaced by its own right child, and then it displaces ${\text{Z}}$ 's position in the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Alternatively, the in-order predecessor can also be used.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode implements the deletion operation in a binary search tree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The ${\text{BST-Delete}}$ procedure deals with the 3 special cases mentioned above.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Lines 2-3 deal with case 1; lines 4-5 deal with case 2 and lines 6-16 for case 3.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The helper function ${\text{Shift-Nodes}}$ is used within the deletion algorithm for the purpose of replacing the node ${\text{u}}$ with ${\text{v}}$ in the binary search tree ${\text{BST}}$ .
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] This procedure handles the deletion (and substitution) of ${\text{u}}$ from ${\text{BST}}$ .
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] A BST can be traversed through three basic algorithms: inorder, preorder, and postorder tree walks.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Following is a recursive implementation of the tree walks.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Without rebalancing, insertions or deletions in a binary search tree may lead to degeneration, resulting in a height n of the tree (where n is number of items in a tree), so that the lookup performance is deteriorated to that of a linear search.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Keeping the search tree balanced and height bounded by $O(\log n)$ is a key to the usefulness of the binary search tree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] This can be achieved by "self-balancing" mechanisms during the updation operations to the tree designed to maintain the tree height to the binary logarithmic complexity.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] A tree is height-balanced if the heights of the left sub-tree and right sub-tree are guaranteed to be related by a constant factor.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] This property was introduced by the AVL tree and continued by the red–black tree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The heights of all the nodes on the path from the root to the modified leaf node have to be observed and possibly corrected on every insert and delete operation to the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] In a weight-balanced tree, the criterion of a balanced tree is the number of leaves of the subtrees.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The weights of the left and right subtrees differ at most by 1 .
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] However, the difference is bound by a ratio $\alpha$ of the weights, since a strong balance condition of 1 cannot be maintained with $O(\log n)$ rebalancing work during insert and delete operations.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] The $\alpha$ -weight-balanced trees gives an entire family of balance conditions, where each left and right subtrees have each at least a fraction of $\alpha$ of the total weight of the subtree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] There are several self-balanced binary search trees, including T-tree, treap, red-black tree, B-tree, 2–3 tree, and Splay tree.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort, where all the elements are inserted at once and the tree is traversed at an in-order fashion.
[src:two-three-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in implementing priority queues, using the node's key as priorities.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In computer science, a **self-balancing binary search tree** (BST) is any node-based binary search tree that automatically keeps its height (maximal number of levels below the root) small in the face of arbitrary item insertions and deletions.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] These operations when designed for a self-balancing binary search tree, contain precautionary measures against boundlessly increasing tree height, so that these abstract data structures receive the attribute "self-balancing".
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For **height-balanced** binary trees, the height is defined to be logarithmic $O(\log n)$ in the number n of items.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] This is the case for many binary search trees, such as AVL trees and red–black trees.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Splay trees and treaps are self-balancing but not height-balanced, as their height is not guaranteed to be logarithmic in the number of items.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing binary search trees provide efficient implementations for mutable ordered lists, and can be used for other abstract data structures such as associative arrays, priority queues and sets.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Most operations on a binary search tree (BST) take time directly proportional to the height of the tree, so it is desirable to keep the height small.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In other words, the minimum height of a binary tree with *n* nodes is log2(*n*), rounded down; that is, $\lfloor \log _{2}n\rfloor$ .
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] However, the simplest algorithms for BST item insertion may yield a tree with height *n* in rather common situations.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For example, when the items are inserted in sorted key order, the tree degenerates into a linked list with *n* nodes.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] The difference in performance between the two situations may be enormous: for example, when *n* = 1,000,000, the minimum height is $\lfloor \log _{2}(1,000,000)\rfloor =19$ .
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] If the data items are known ahead of time, the height can be kept small, in the average sense, by adding values in a random order, resulting in a random binary search tree.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] However, there are many situations (such as online algorithms) where this randomization is not viable.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing binary trees solve this problem by performing transformations on the tree (such as tree rotations) at key insertion times, in order to keep the height proportional to log2(*n*).
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Although a certain overhead is involved, it is not bigger than the always necessary lookup cost and may be justified by ensuring fast execution of all operations.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] While it is possible to maintain a BST with minimum height with expected $O(\log n)$ time operations (lookup/insertion/removal), the additional space requirements required to maintain such a structure tend to outweigh the decrease in search time.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For comparison, an AVL tree is guaranteed to be within a factor of 1.44 of the optimal height while requiring only two additional bits of storage in a naive implementation.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Therefore, most self-balancing BST algorithms keep the height within a constant factor of this lower bound.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In the asymptotic ("Big-O") sense, a self-balancing BST structure containing *n* items allows the lookup, insertion, and removal of an item in $O(\log n)$ worst-case time, and ordered enumeration of all items in $O(n)$ time.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For some implementations these are per-operation time bounds, while for others they are amortized bounds over a sequence of operations.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] These times are asymptotically optimal among all data structures that manipulate the key only through comparisons.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing binary search trees can be used in a natural way to construct and maintain ordered lists, such as priority queues.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] They can also be used for associative arrays; key-value pairs are simply inserted with an ordering based on the key alone.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In this capacity, self-balancing BSTs have a number of advantages and disadvantages over their main competitor, hash tables.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] One advantage of self-balancing BSTs is that they allow fast (indeed, asymptotically optimal) enumeration of the items *in key order*, which hash tables do not provide.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] One disadvantage is that their lookup algorithms get more complicated when there may be multiple items with the same key.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing BSTs have better worst-case lookup performance than most hash tables ( $O(\log n)$ compared to $O(n)$ ), but have worse average-case performance ( $O(\log n)$ compared to $O(1)$ ).
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing BSTs can be used to implement any algorithm that requires mutable ordered lists, to achieve optimal worst-case asymptotic performance.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For example, if binary tree sort is implemented with a self-balancing BST, we have a very simple-to-describe yet asymptotically optimal $O(n\log n)$ sorting algorithm.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Similarly, many algorithms in computational geometry exploit variations on self-balancing BSTs to solve problems such as the line segment intersection problem and the point location problem efficiently.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] (For average-case performance, however, self-balancing BSTs may be less efficient than other solutions.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing BSTs are flexible data structures, in that it is easy to extend them to efficiently record additional information or perform new operations.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For example, one can record the number of nodes in each subtree having a certain property, allowing one to count the number of nodes in a certain key range with that property in $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:two-three-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] These extensions can be used, for example, to optimize database queries or other list-processing algorithms.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] In discrete mathematics, **tree rotation** is an operation on a binary tree that changes the structure without interfering with the order of the elements.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] A tree rotation moves one node up in the tree and one node down.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] It is used to change the shape of the tree, and in particular to decrease its height by moving smaller subtrees down and larger subtrees up, resulting in improved performance of many tree operations.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] There exists an inconsistency in different descriptions as to the definition of the **direction of rotations**.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] This article takes the approach of the directional movement of the rotating node.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] The right rotation operation as shown in the adjacent image is performed with *Q* as the root and hence is a right rotation on, or rooted at, *Q*.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] This operation results in a rotation of the tree in the clockwise direction.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] The inverse operation is the left rotation, which results in a movement in a counter-clockwise direction (the left rotation shown above is rooted at *P*).
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] The key to understanding how a rotation functions is to understand its constraints.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] In particular the order of the leaves of the tree (when read left to right for example) cannot change (another way to think of it is that the order that the leaves would be visited in an in-order traversal must be the same after the operation as before).
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Another constraint is the main property of a binary search tree, namely that all nodes in the right subtree are greater than the parent and all nodes in the left subtree are less than the parent.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Notice that the right child of a left child of the root of a sub-tree (for example node B in the diagram for the tree rooted at Q) can become the left child of the root, that itself becomes the right child of the "new" root in the rotated sub-tree, without violating either of those constraints.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] As seen in the diagram, the order of the leaves doesn't change.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] The opposite operation also preserves the order and is the second kind of rotation.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Assuming this is a binary search tree, as stated above, the elements must be interpreted as variables that can be compared to each other.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] The alphabetic characters to the left are used as placeholders for these variables.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] In the animation to the right, capital alphabetic characters are used as variable placeholders while lowercase Greek letters are placeholders for an entire set of variables.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] The circles represent individual nodes and the triangles represent subtrees.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Each subtree could be empty, consist of a single node, or consist of any number of nodes.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] When a subtree is rotated, the subtree side upon which it is rotated increases its height by one node while the other subtree decreases its height.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] This makes tree rotations useful for rebalancing a tree.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Consider the terminology of **Root** for the parent node of the subtrees to rotate, **Pivot** for the node which will become the new parent node, **RS** for the side of rotation and **OS** for the opposite side of rotation.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] For the root Q in the diagram above, **RS** is C and **OS** is P.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] The programmer must also make sure that the root's parent points to the pivot after the rotation.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Also, the programmer should note that this operation may result in a new root for the entire tree and take care to update pointers accordingly.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] The tree rotation renders the inorder traversal of the binary tree invariant.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] This implies the order of the elements is not affected when a rotation is performed in any part of the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Computing one from the other is very simple.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] There are also *double rotations*, which are combinations of left and right rotations.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] A *double left* rotation at X can be defined to be a right rotation at the right child of X followed by a left rotation at X; similarly, a *double right* rotation at X can be defined to be a left rotation at the left child of X followed by a right rotation at X.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Tree rotations are used in a number of tree data structures such as AVL trees, red–black trees, WAVL trees, splay trees, and treaps.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] They require only constant time because they are *local* transformations: they only operate on 5 nodes, and need not examine the rest of the tree.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] A tree can be rebalanced using rotations.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] After a rotation, the side of the rotation increases its height by 1 whilst the side opposite the rotation decreases its height similarly.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Therefore, one can strategically apply rotations to nodes whose left child and right child differ in height by more than 1.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Self-balancing binary search trees apply this operation automatically.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] A type of tree which uses this rebalancing technique is the AVL tree.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Can the rotation distance between two binary trees be computed in polynomial time?
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] The rotation distance between any two binary trees with the same number of nodes is the minimum number of rotations needed to transform one into the other.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] With this distance, the set of *n*-node binary trees becomes a metric space: the distance is symmetric, positive when given two different trees, and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] It is an open problem whether there exists a polynomial time algorithm for calculating rotation distance, though several variants of the rotation distance problem admit polynomial time algorithms.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Daniel Sleator, Robert Tarjan and William Thurston showed that the rotation distance between any two *n*-node trees (for *n* ≥ 11) is at most 2*n* − 6, and that some pairs of trees are this far apart as soon as *n* is sufficiently large.
[src:two-three-tree/tree-rotation] Lionel Pournin showed that, in fact, such pairs exist whenever *n* ≥ 11.
